#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/traction-eos/references/data.md
M|references|The Data Component replaces gut-feeling management with objective, weekly numbers. When everyone in the leadership team looks at the same 5-15 metrics every week, problems surface weeks earlier, accou
M|references|A Scorecard is a one-page doc that tracks 5-15 activity-based numbers weekly. It is rv in every Level 10 meeting. If a number is off track, it drops to the Issues List for IDS.
M|references|1. **Weekly cadence.** Monthly financials are too slow. By the time you see a monthly miss, you have lost four weeks of correction time. Weekly numbers give you early warning.
M|references|2. **Activity-based metrics.** Measure what people do (calls made, demos given), not just what happened (revenue, churn). Activities are leading indicators you can influence. Results are lagging indic
M|references|3. **5-15 numbers.** Fewer than 5 means blind spots. More than 15 means noise. Most companies land on 8-12.
M|references|4. **Every number has an owner.** One person is accountable for each metric. Not a department. A name.
M|references|5. **Every number has a goal.** A number without a goal is just a data point. The goal creates the standard for red/green tracking.
M|references|Ask yourself: "If I went on vacation for four weeks with no phone or email, what 5-15 numbers would I want to see when I got back to know exactly how the business performed?"
M|references|This question forces you to identify the vital few numbers that genuinely indicate business health.
M|references|| Category | What to Measure | Example Metrics |
M|references||----------|----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| **Revenue** | Money coming in | Weekly revenue, new deal value, average deal size |
M|references|| **pl** | Future revenue | New leads generated, qualified opportunities, proposals sent |
M|references|| **Sales Activity** | Effort going in | Calls made, demos completed, meetings booked |
M|references|| **Customer Health** | Retention and satisfaction | Churn rate, NPS, support tickets resolved, renewal rate |
M|references|| **Operations** | Delivery quality | On-time delivery %, defect rate, utilization rate |
M|references|| **Financial** | Cash and profitability | Cash balance, AR over 60 days, gross margin |
M|references|| **People** | Team health | Open positions, employee satisfaction score, training hours |
M|references|Understanding the difference between leading and lagging indicators is critical to building an effective Scorecard.
M|references|| Type | Definition | rsp Time | Examples |
M|references||------|-----------|--------------|---------|
M|references|| **Leading** | Measures input activities that drive future results | Can be corrected this week | Calls made, proposals sent, cnt published |
M|references|| **Lagging** | Measures output results that have already occurred | Can only be observed, not changed retroactively | Revenue, churn, profit margin |
M|references|**The ideal Scorecard is 70% leading indicators and 30% lagging indicators.** Leading indicators let you course-correct before lagging indicators go red.
M|references|Great Scorecards show the cause-and-effect chain from activity to result:
M|references|```
M|references|Outbound emails (leading)
M|references|→ Meetings booked (leading)
M|references|→ Demos given (leading)
M|references|→ Proposals sent (leading)
M|references|→ Deals closed (lagging)
M|references|→ Revenue (lagging)
M|references|```
M|references|When revenue drops, you can trace back through the chain to find where the breakdown occurred. Was it fewer emails? Lower meeting conversion? Longer sales cycles? The Scorecard tells you.
M|references|Each metric on the Scorecard is assigned to one person. That person:
M|references|- Reports the number weekly in the Level 10 meeting
M|references|- Explains when the number is off track
M|references|- Owns the plan to get it back on track
M|references|- Drops it to the Issues List when help is needed
M|references|**Ownership does not mean they do all the work.** The VP of Sales owns the "demos completed" metric even though individual reps give the demos. Ownership means accountability for the result.
M|references|| Metric | Owner | Why |
M|references||--------|-------|-----|
M|references|| Weekly revenue | Head of Sales | Directly manages the revenue-generating team |
M|references|| New leads | Head of mkt | Responsible for lead generation str |
M|references|| On-time delivery | Head of Operations | Manages delivery team and processes |
M|references|| Cash balance | Head of fin | Manages cash flow and collections |
M|references|| Employee satisfaction | Head of People/Integrator | Responsible for culture and retention |
M|references|Goals should be based on:
M|references|- **Historical performance:** What have you averaged over the past 13 weeks?
M|references|- **Growth targets:** What does the 1-Year Plan require?
M|references|- **Capacity:** What is realistically achievable with current resources?
M|references|| Metric | 13-Week Average | 1-Year Plan Requires | Goal |
M|references||--------|----------------|---------------------|------|
M|references|| Weekly revenue | $42K | $60K/week by Q4 | $45K (Q1), $50K (Q2), $55K (Q3), $60K (Q4) |
M|references|| New leads | 80 | 120/week | 90 (Q1), 100 (Q2), 110 (Q3), 120 (Q4) |
M|references|| Demos completed | 15 | 25/week | 18 (Q1), 20 (Q2), 22 (Q3), 25 (Q4) |
M|references|Goals can be updated quarterly during the Quarterly ses. Do not change them mid-quarter unless the business model fundamentally changes.
M|references|Each week, every metric is marked as green (on track) or red (off track):
M|references|- **Green:** Number meets or exceeds the goal
M|references|- **Red:** Number misses the goal
M|references|When a number is red, the owner has two options:
M|references|1. **Explain and fix:** The issue is understood and a correction is underway
M|references|2. **Drop to IDS:** The issue needs the team's input to solve
M|references|| Metric | Owner | Goal | W1 | W2 | W3 | W4 | W5 | W6 | W7 | W8 | W9 | W10 | W11 | W12 | W13 |
M|references||--------|-------|------|----|----|----|----|----|----|----|----|----|----|-----|-----|-----|
M|references|| Revenue | Pat | $50K | G | G | R | G | G | G | R | G | G | G | G | G | G |
M|references|| Leads | Alex | 100 | G | R | R | G | G | G | G | G | G | R | G | G | G |
M|references|| Demos | Jordan | 20 | G | G | G | G | R | G | G | G | G | G | G | R | G |
M|references|**The 13-week trailing view** is essential. It shows trends, not just snapshots. Three consecutive red weeks on the same metric is a systemic issue that must be IDS'd.
M|references|| Metric | Owner | Goal | Frequency |
M|references||--------|-------|------|-----------|
M|references|| New qualified leads | SDR Manager | 50/week | Weekly |
M|references|| Discovery calls completed | Sales Manager | 25/week | Weekly |
M|references|| Proposals sent | Sales Manager | 10/week | Weekly |
M|references|| Deals closed | Sales Manager | 5/week | Weekly |
M|references|| New revenue booked | VP Sales | $75K/week | Weekly |
M|references|| pl value | VP Sales | $500K+ | Weekly |
M|references|| Win rate | VP Sales | >25% | Weekly |
M|references|| Metric | Owner | Goal | Frequency |
M|references||--------|-------|------|-----------|
M|references|| Website visitors | mkt Manager | 5,000/week | Weekly |
M|references|| cnt pieces published | cnt Lead | 3/week | Weekly |
M|references|| MQLs generated | Demand Gen Lead | 100/week | Weekly |
M|references|| Email open rate | Email Manager | >25% | Weekly |
M|references|| soc engagement | soc Lead | 500 interactions/week | Weekly |
M|references|| Cost per lead | VP mkt | <$50 | Weekly |
M|references|| Metric | Owner | Goal | Frequency |
M|references||--------|-------|------|-----------|
M|references|| Projects delivered on time | Project Manager | >90% | Weekly |
M|references|| Customer satisfaction (CSAT) | Support Lead | >4.5/5 | Weekly |
M|references|| Support tickets resolved | Support Lead | <24hr avg | Weekly |
M|references|| Utilization rate | Operations Manager | 75-85% | Weekly |
M|references|| Quality issues | QA Lead | <3/week | Weekly |
M|references|| Capacity available | Operations Manager | >15% buffer | Weekly |
M|references|| Metric | Owner | Goal | Frequency |
M|references||--------|-------|------|-----------|
M|references|| Cash balance | Controller | >$300K | Weekly |
M|references|| AR over 60 days | AR Manager | <$50K | Weekly |
M|references|| Weekly cash burn | CFO | <$40K | Weekly |
M|references|| Invoices sent within 48hr | AR Manager | 100% | Weekly |
M|references|| Payroll accuracy | Payroll Lead | 100% | Weekly |
M|references|| Mistake | Why It Hurts | Fix |
M|references||---------|-------------|-----|
M|references|| **Too many metrics (>15)** | Information overload, no focus | Cut to the vital few that indicate health |
M|references|| **All lagging indicators** | Cannot course-correct, only observe | Add leading indicators: activities and inputs |
M|references|| **No owner assigned** | "Someone will handle it" means nobody does | One name per metric, no exceptions |
M|references|| **Goals too easy** | Scorecard is always green, masks problems | Set goals that require effort but are achievable |
M|references|| **Goals too hard** | Scorecard is always red, creates learned helplessness | Base goals on 13-week average plus realistic stretch |
M|references|| **Not rv weekly** | Data goes stale, accountability disappears | Scorecard is agenda item #2 in every Level 10 meeting |
M|references|| **Monthly instead of weekly** | Lose 4 weeks of correction time | Convert monthly metrics to weekly proxies |
M|references|| **Vanity metrics** | Numbers that look good but do not drive the business | Replace with metrics tied to revenue or customer outcomes |
M|references|| **No trending view** | See this week but miss the pattern | Always show 13 trailing weeks |
M|references|| **Changing metrics too often** | No baseline for comparison | Lock metrics for at least one full quarter |
M|references|**Activity-based metrics** are best when:
M|references|- You need early warning signals
M|references|- You want to influence behavior
M|references|- The sales cycle is long (weeks or months)
M|references|- You are building new processes
M|references|**Results-based metrics** are best when:
M|references|- You need to confirm the activities are producing outcomes
M|references|- You are reporting to a board or investors
M|references|- The metric is a business health vital sign (cash, churn, revenue)
M|references|```
M|references|LEADING (Activities)          LAGGING (Results)
M|references|├── Calls made                ├── Revenue
M|references|├── Demos given               ├── Profit margin
M|references|├── Proposals sent            ├── Customer churn
M|references|├── cnt published         ├── NPS score
M|references|├── Candidates interviewed    └── Cash balance
M|references|└── Tickets resolved
M|references|```
M|references|A healthy Scorecard has both types in roughly a 70/30 split favoring leading indicators.
M|references|The Scorecard is rv in the first 5 minutes of the Level 10 meeting, right after the Segue. Here is the protocol:
M|references|1. **Display the Scorecard** so all attendees can see it (projector, shared screen, or printed)
M|references|2. **Go metric by metric.** The owner reads the number and states "on track" or "off track."
M|references|3. **No discussion during rv.** If a number is off track, the owner simply states the number and says "dropping to Issues List."
M|references|4. **Time limit: 5 minutes.** This is a quick scan, not a deep dive. Deep dives happen during IDS.
M|references|5. **Pattern recognition.** If the same metric is red three weeks in a row, it is automatically the top issue for IDS.
M|references|When a metric is off track, the flow is:
M|references|```
M|references|Scorecard rv → Metric is red → Owner drops to Issues List
M|references|→ During IDS, team identifies root cause
M|references|→ Action items assigned (who, what, by when)
M|references|→ Next week: check if action item is complete
M|references|→ Check if metric returned to green
M|references|```
M|references|This weekly cycle ensures no problem goes unaddressed for more than one week. The Scorecard is the early warning system. The Level 10 meeting is the rsp mechanism.
M|references|- [ ] Brainstorm 20-30 possible metrics with the leadership team
M|references|- [ ] Apply the vacation test to narrow to 5-15
M|references|- [ ] Assign one owner per metric
M|references|- [ ] Set goals based on 13-week historical average plus 10% stretch
M|references|- [ ] Create a simple spreadsheet with 13 trailing weeks
M|references|- [ ] Commit to reviewing it in the next Level 10 meeting
M|references|- [ ] Remove metrics that are always green (too easy or not meaningful)
M|references|- [ ] Replace metrics that nobody understands
M|references|- [ ] Adjust goals that were set too high or too low
M|references|- [ ] Ensure every department has at least one metric on the Scorecard
M|references|- [ ] Everyone can recite the Scorecard metrics from mem
M|references|- [ ] The team looks forward to Scorecard rv (it creates clarity)
M|references|- [ ] Off-track metrics are solved quickly through IDS
M|references|- [ ] New hires are shown the Scorecard in their first week
M|references|- [ ] Department-level scorecards cascade from the company Scorecard